title: Program Transformers: Return multiple program elements. Plus: Taclet for pulling out initializer from for loop.
description:
Program Transformers: Return multiple program elements. Plus: Taclet for pulling out initializer from for loop.

# Why? 

Before, ProgramTransformers could only return one ProgramElement, which was sometimes awkward (e.g. for the new taclet which is also included in this branch). The new taclet pulls out the initializer of a for loop and can later on be interesting (we're currently working on new loop invariant taclets with a Bachelor Thesis student).

# Features and Impact

New taclet, ability of transformers to return multiple (e.g.) statements.
 
Changed the KeY core (ProgramTransformer and related classes).

No impact for using KeY or build scripts.

# Review

> Are there any places that should be reviewed more closely?

Should basically be fine.

# Persons involved

Dominic Steinhöfel. Taclet by Benedikt Dreher.

title: fixing a bug resulting in NPEs while pretty printing
description:
reported by Jelle @jkuebler.

If an observer is applied to "null", then pretty printing failed blatantly.

The legal (yet not valid) sequent `x=null ==> x.size() = 5` can be rewritten using `applyEq` as
`x=null ==> null.size() = 5` which recoder does not exactly like.

This "fix" catches the exception and ignores it.

title: Block and Loop Contracts (created new merge request, since old one seems to be in zombie mode aka does not respond anymore)
description:
This merge provides the a new rule for JavaDL that allows the user
to divide a method into blocks whose correctness may be proven
independently of the method’s correctness. The rule is based on
the previous block contract rule, including some bugfixes and amendments.
Another rule provided with this merge is the loop contract rule, for
more information on loop contracts, see the paper by Thomas Tuerk (2012).

In a nutshell, loops are considered as tail-recursive functions
and may thus be specified using pre- and postconditions, and more
fine-grained framing conditions.
Illustrative examples are added to the KeY example menu to be found
in the menu point "Dynamic Frames".

Furthermore, the JML-keyword "\before()" is introduced, which refers
to the state before the last loop iteration or in the beginning of the
block (with this change, the keyword "\old()" now consistently refers
to the method's prestate, also in block contracts).
More details can be seen in Florian Lanzinger's bachelor thesis.

title: first stage of #1457: additional source code area and tracking the state of symbolic execution
description:
The implementation of the first stage of #1457 is done.
Implemented changes are:
- [x] Additional area (can be hidden) to the right of the sequent view which shows the source code relevant for the current node. Multiple source code files are supported by adding a separate tab for each file.
- [x] Lines which were symbolically executed up to the current node are highlighted (yellow).
- [x] Highlights can be clicked to jump to the node where the symbolic execution touched them last. The most recently executed line is highlighted in a more saturated color.
- [x] Basic syntax highlighting is enabled in the source view.
- [x] A StatusBar is displayed below the source code to show the nature of the current branch (Invariant initially valid, Body Preserves Invariant, Null Pointer Case, ...).

The idea is to merge these changes into master to get feedback and get an idea which changes/additions are required by the users of KeY.

Ideas for the second stage:
- [x] Improve/debug syntax highlighting (JML-Keywords!).
-  ~~Visualize in which case we are in If/Else by underlining/striking out the statement.~~
-  ~~Handle multiple versions of a source code file (prerequisite for editing. -> see #1468~~
-  ~~Enable source code editing directly in the newly created text area.~~

title: fix for #831: Enabled Pruning and GoalBack in closed branches/proofs
description:
Changing closed branches/proofs is possible with the changes introduced by this branch. This includes pruning as well as undoing the most recently applied rule.

A drawback is the increased memory consumption, since now all nodes have to be stored even for closed branches.
However, our comparison showed that even for large proofs (tested with PairInsertionSort_sort.proof, which can be found at the bottom of https://www.key-project.org/2017/08/17/dual-pivot/) with about 300.000 nodes there is only about 150 MB additional memory used. This seems acceptable with current hardware.

If you are short at memory it is possible to start KeY with the newly introduced flag `--no-pruning-closed` , which completely disables the new feature (as well as the additional memory consumption) and restores the old behavior.

Heatmap-style highlighting of sequent formulas or terms.

# Features and Impact

The heatmap feature allows highlighting of the most recently changed terms and sequent formulas in the sequent view. This can be used e.g. to distinguish the last formula that was worked on in a sequent, or to show on which parts of the sequent the auto-mode worked.

# Review

The existing infrastructure of the CurrentGoalView has been used. I would be grateful for comments on the code structure in that class (should some of the code be moved somewhere else?).
Additionaly, I would appreciate feedback concerning the overall functionality, and as to whether the feature behaves like a user would expect.

title: fix for #412 -> preserve branch labels when pruning
description:
When pruning branches (which is for example done by the macro CloseProvableGoalsBelow) the NodeInfo object storing the branch label is deleted. This is because the GUIBranchNode gets its label from the NodeInfo object attached to the **next** Node in the tree. This Node however is cleared by the pruning and so its NodeInfo.

The solution is to temporary store the branch label and reassign it after the NodeInfo object has been cleared.

title: Schiffl search filter
description:
New filter functionality enhances the search function by hiding or regrouping sequent formulas.

# Features and Impact

This branch contains improvements of the search function in the Sequent View of the KeY GUI. It enables the user to choose how the search results are filtered. Default is highlighting only (as before). When "Hide" is selected, all sequent formulas not matching the search are hidden. "Regroup" puts all matching formulas around the sequent arrow, allowing the user to have all the interesting parts of the sequent in one place.
Exiting the search, e.g. via Esc-Key, restores the original sequent. Whenever a new sequent view is created, the filter is automatically reset to the default Highlight filter.

# Review

The search filter class was developed utilising the already existing sequentPrintFilter interface, which was adapted to accomodate the new functionality.
During development, the idea to merge the CurrentGoalView and InnerNodeView classes came up, but was dismissed for the time being. This might still be a good idea in the future

# Persons involved

Development by Jonas Schiffl, in close coordination with and guided by Mattias Ulbrich
